                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d733">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-23T21:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 23, 1942—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 24—9:09 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>302. I left with de Gaulle today a paraphrase of the Department’s 136, August
                        21.<note n="51" xml:id="d733fn51">See footnote 49, <ref target="#pg_619">p.
                            619</ref>.</note> De Gaulle will soon address me a note containing his
                    observations. He expressed his great satisfaction that the United States
                    Government is taking an active interest in the present difficulty. He said he
                    was somewhat pained that the Department appeared somewhat to doubt sincerity of
                    the French spheres [<hi rend="italic">promises of?</hi>] independence. It is
                    quite possible that he will request American mediation.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Cairo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gwynn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
